  "prompt": "Graph Theory: What does it mean if vertices are adjacent?",
  "response": "In graph theory, two vertices (or nodes) are said to be **adjacent** if there is an edge (or connection) directly linking them. This means that the two vertices are directly connected in the graph structure. \n\nFor example, in an undirected graph, if there is an edge between vertex \\(A\\) and vertex \\(B\\), then \\(A\\) and \\(B\\) are considered adjacent. In a directed graph, adjacency can depend on the direction of the edges; vertex \\(A\\) would be adjacent to vertex \\(B\\) if there is a directed edge from \\(A\\) to \\(B\\).\n\nTo summarize, adjacency indicates a direct relationship or connection between two vertices in a graph.",
